he United States offer a fresh and nuanced image of the religious reform movements on the Italian peninsula in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. United in their conviction that religious ideas can only be fully understood in relation to the particular social, cultural, and political contexts in which they develop, these scholars explore a wide range of protagonists from popes, bishops, and inquisitors to humanists and merchants, to artists, jewelers, and nuns. What emerges is a story of negotiations, mediations, compromises, and of shifting boundaries between heresy and orthodoxy. This book is essential reading for all students of the history of Christianity in early modern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh1 aBonora, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelph, Ronald K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelph, Ronald K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFirpo, Massimo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Michelle M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Michelle M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFragnito, Gigliola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrendler, Paul F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson Schutte, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffries Martin, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeathers Kuntz, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, John Jeffries, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGinness, Frederick J., econt